{
  "doc_id": "60197",
  "text": "An additional weakness of species distribution models is that they describe present species -environment correlations, which do not necessarily reflect causal relationships [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Spurious correlations will lead to erroneous predictions if changes do not occur in unison. Species may shift in abundance through space and time at different rates because they have different dispersal abilities and thermal sensitivities and use a variety of phenological cues [CITATION_3] . In turn, interactions between coexisting species may change, and novel communities may form as extant species reshuffle or as species colonize new areas [CITATION_4] .",
